description.text:
Heres a mold I made for my HE280/Rostock Max v2/3 from seemecnc. Havent tested the more 'elaborate' version, but thats curing at the moment.

V1 files worked great, but decided i could do better. So v2/non marked should stay on a bit better. Will post pics tomorrow, hopefully.

Rotate files to sit better on the bed. I think each just needs a 90° rotation around the X axis, but you can figure out the best way to print each thing, right? :)

Hmm... Still on the fence on how i want to make this thing better. Its a bit hard to ensure the core is centered in the mold, without making going to a multiple piece mold and stuff. But then again... ive already got 2+core as is.

For the actual silicone, I didnt bother getting whatever 2 part silicone mold stuff. Do it on the cheap and get a tube of 100% silicone caulk, and some dawn dish soap (or glycerin from a drug store). Mix some in with a bowl of water, put some caulk into the water, knead by hand for a few mins. It will start to turn white-ish. Dunk the mold pieces in the water to act as a release, put a glob inside the bottom (bigger piece), ram the core down in and push it on its post, then make sure the top is covered, and put the top piece on.

Wait a few hours (i waited a full 24 for good measure) and open it up. It should hopefully come out fairly easy with a spatula or some other thin object.
Trim the top of the silicone away (to basically whats shown as blue in the image), and carefully slide it/strech it out and around the core. After, give it a bit to ensure any residual water/etc has dried, and then put it on your hotend. Bam. cheap silicone sock/heater block cover.

To get a better fit, i cut a slot in the cover to route the thermister wires through, undid the screw, pushed them through (and the cover up towards the pcb), then put the thermister back in, slid the cover down and its done.

Video by Crussty/Practical Printing, on how to actually do this.

What is Docky?

Update 5/17/2017: Check out Docky review via youtuber and thingiverse user Rawdilz: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jU5JQAN596U

Update 5/9/2017: Added Docky no cover versions, Docky with no hinges and no need to use the cover. (This was a user request I'm not sure about stability of this model and I have not printed it, use at your own risk)

Update 5/1/2017: Added power led indicator and front bevel to switch docking area, rebuilt 3D model from scratch with better proportions.

Docky is a pocket size custom 3D model you can print and use as an enclosure for the internal components of your OEM Nintendo Switch Dock.

Dimensions are as follows:

  • Docky Top:

    • Width: 67.36mm
    • Height: 20.70mm
    • Depth: 105mm

  • Docky Cover:

    • Width: 70.76mm
    • Height: 20.70mm
    • Depth: 34.78mm
  • Docky Bottom:
    • Width: 61.43mm
    • Height: 10.00mm
    • Depth: 99.37mm

What did you use to build this model?

I used Blender to make this 3D model.

Files for 3D Printing

Files for 3D printing are in the STL folder:

  • docky-bottom.stl
  • docky-cover-beveled.stl (Docky cover is beveled)
  • docky-cover-embossed.stl (Docky logo is embossed)
  • docky-cover.stl (No logo)
  • docky-top-beveled.stl (Nintendo Switch logo beveled)
  • docky-top-embossed.stl (Nintendo Switch logo embossed)
  • docky-top.stl (No logo, add your own if you want)
  • docky-top-no-cover.stl (No logo and no cover hinges, add your own if you want)
  • docky-top-no-cover-beveled.stl (Nintendo Switch logo beveled and no cover hinges)
  • docky-top-no-cover-embossed.stl (Nintendo Switch logo embossed and no cover hinges)

Tools and Items Needed

  1. Tri-Point Screwdriver - I recommend this kit
  2. 1 Nintendo Switch Dock
  3. 9 OEM Nintendo Dock Screws
  4. 2 USB-C OEM Nintendo Dock Screws
  5. Docky STL files

Instructions on how to open your Nintendo Switch Dock

Installing the Motherboard in Docky

  1. You should have all 3 Docky components
  2. Place the motherboard and fold a piece of the ribbon and put it under the usb ports so when you secure the motherboard the pressure keeps the ribbon in place. Secure the motherboard in the bottom Docky component with 5 screws.

  3. Place the led board into the crevice in the bottom component and apply some pressure until it's pretty firm.
  4. Place usb-c port and tighten the 2 screws.
  5. With the bottom component fully assembled insert the side with the HDMI, usb and power ports into the top Docky component first, apply a little pressure.

  6. Proceed to insert the other side with the 2 usb ports by lifting a bit the plastic so you can slide the bottom Docky component into the top component.
  7. Tighten the bottom Docky component with 4 screws.

  8. Install the cover by placing one end into the top Docky component and then sliding the other end until it seats firmly.
  9. Your shiny new pocket size Docky is ready to go.

This object started out as a means to create a test object for another project, but after realizing the difficulty of creating a modular tangential cylinders arranged such that all of them touch the next one for n =/= 4, I decided to program a more versatile object in case I ever needed to use it for something else. Plus the math looks way more pretty. I thought I was going to need calculus because I was using the tangent of an ellipse in my original experiment, but I was able to figure it out using angles from the perspective of a projection.

Play with it, feel free to ask questions, I'll be posting more now that I finally made an account. I've got a back log of beautiful geometry to upload.

i will edit this section later if I have time.

Essentially, I used the rise angle for the cylinder /_ when viewed in the plane of ZY, and tried to find the vertical distance (h) from the center of one rod to the center of the rod above it, at the distance it's being rotated. Since the point of contact is NOT in that line, you need to view it along one of the rods, so then I transformed the angles to match the projection of the image along those rods using a normal line. That results in alpha (the angle between the current rod and the next rod when viewed by rotating from the ZY-plane about the Z axis by beta, and then when rotated about the Y axis by theta (or 90-theta since I made that kind of messy). Then angle w is the angle that the next rod goes into the plane, perpendicular to the viewing plane, and originating from the same point as angle alpha... So basically you use the fact that you're now viewing it down the rod, and that the center to center distance between the rods in this projection is 2*r, then you finagle some messy trigonometry around that to get k, which is the projection of the distance between the points on the rod that are vertical to each other in the original view (and are in the projection too) and then you use angles alpha and w to finagle the real length of a bunch of lines to ultimately get h. You take that, and transform it into the distance you have to translate the cylinder when rotating it by theta so that they're parallel, and then with those really simple numbers you just move a bunch of cylinders that distance out, rotated by thetadegrees, and rotate N of them by 360.N degrees about Z. boom. I probably could do a video explaining that and it would make more sense. I mean, visualizing 3D stuff in 2D is hard enough, but visualizing it with no drawings is like, yeah.

description.text:
This is Hugo. Named after Hugo de Vries who introduced the term "mutation". First of I would like to thank Joachim (jsturm) who started this project in the first place and did almost the entire testing of the parts. The entire design is done in OpenSCAD and all files are hosted on https://github.com/kr2/Hugo. At the moment we have two running Hugo Printers.
The red one is an Hugo_standard, which was built by JStrum. Printed mostly in PLA on an old Mendel. He made it on purpose as small as possible to fit on his desk (so it has not the metrics one finds in the corresponding config file). The black one is an Hugo+, build by me (KR2) and printed on an Prusa in ABS. The Design is a derivative of the original Printrbot by abdrumm, but all parts are redesigned and improved.

First of two things:
It is always recommend to check the .stl files before printing. If you have problems slicing the stl files with Slic3r try fixing them with http://cloud.netfabb.com/ (for Skeinforge the files should work out of the box). If you find bugs plz add them here: https://github.com/kr2/Hugo/issues +--------------------------------------+ Links:
  • GitHub: https://github.com/kr2/Hugo
  • Wiki: http://reprap.org/wiki/Hugo //still under construction
  • Youtube 1 (Hugo_standard): http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xLbd4vq-afk
  • Youtube 2 (Hugo_standard): http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mVCLkyvZX7M
    • +--------------------------------------+ So at the moment there are three OpenSCAD configuration files for Hugo_improved, pb_standard, Hugo_standard and Hugo+. You find the corresponding .stl files in the zip archives. Beneath is a short description of the variations, for a bit more detail check out https://github.com/kr2/Hugo/blob/release/src/config.scad and https://github.com/kr2/Hugo/tree/release/src/config. Hugo_improved [recommend] is set up for HTD 3M belts on 3M 12 teeth Pulleys (3M/12) and it also has an increased x axis distance compared to the pb_standard (25.38 mm vs 32 mm). The Hugo_standard is the same as the pb_standard (see below) only that it is set up for T2.5 Belts and corresponding Pulleys with 20 Teeth (T2.5/20). The Hugo+ (HugoPlus) has some major changes. It is designed for T2.5 belt and 12 teeth Pulleys (T2.5/12) and Z Axis with an diameter of 12 mm. The distance of the X-Axis is also increased and the default settings are set for an Printvoulme of 300x300x300 mm. The pb_standard has almost everywhere the same dimensions as the Printrbot so, it is not recommend, but one should be able to combine parts from the printrbot and the Hugo(pb_standard). The pb_standard parts alone should fit together but since the original printrbot parts partly doesn't fit together in an sound way plz don't expect that hugo replacement parts for an existing Printrbot fix that problem. But since at the beginning of all Hugo source files there is an section where you can set the dimensions of the part, so you can try to go there and enter your needed dimensions.

title: Ultimaker 2 Door parts
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I wanted a door on my Ultimaker 2+ clone, but didn't want to modify the printerframe.

The parts are fixed using the original 3 screws in the front side of the frame. Just replace the existing screws with m3 20mm versions.

I've uploaded the files for use with door mounted on both left and right side along with STEP file if you want to change something.

Door knob
I didn't like the magnetic doorhandle used by my source of inspiration (see "How I designed this"), so I'm instead using this door knob: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1777101 which I printed in PETG at 0.15mm layer height.
Note: You need to drill a ø20mm hole through the acrylic plate to use this knob.
Mine clipped together nicely, so didn't screw it together. Can always do it later.

Printer:

My Crossbot design

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0,15

Infill:

25

Notes:

I've printed in black PETG with 3 borders and 25% infill for strength.

3-4 top and bottom layers

I was inspired by https://www.youmagine.com/designs/ultimaker-2-front-door-with-hidden-magnetic-catch
I drew my hinges in Fusion 360 for 3mm metal rods instead of his 5mm rods.

There are a bunch of other hard to see changes, but which strengthen the parts and enables the door to go to the edge of the front panel.

• 3x m3 nuts
  • 3x m3 8mm screws
  • 3x m3 20mm screws to replace the 3 side screws of your printer-frame
  • 3x ø3 15mm rods - I used one from old cd/dvd drive and cut it using dremel

Acrylic plate

  • I used 3mm plate, as that was what I had, but it leaves a small gap (I just noticed), so 5mm would fit better. I'll make an insert to put between the acrylic parts and the hinges
  • 29,5cm high - this is important as it is below the lettering and well above the knob, but still cover the opening perfectly.
  • 31cm width. You can make it 32,5cm if you want it to go all the way across

You need to countersink the heads of the m3 8mm screws into your acrylic plate.

Do 3mm holes for your screws and then use an 8mm metal drill to carefully drill down untill the head of the screws doesn't stick out.

Use a dull drill if you have one, and be carefull it doesn't just chew up your plate.

description.text:
I have an HD projector, that I wanted to mount to the ceiling. Problem is, most projector mount are specific, needing a specific mounting plate. So I put this one together, making it generic.

It is inspired by Wade's design, which gave me a great starting point, but needed to be a bit more secure and made generic. The original is here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4146

Firstly, I added a ceiling securing ring which can be used (as an additional item) to add support for particularly heavy items. Simply drill holes in the ceiling, and from the upstairs floor void slip the ring on the bolts and tighten them.

Wade's original design had 1 flaw in that the Projector Plate is specific, so I separated the plate into a Plate Mount, and separate Plate which fasten together using 4 x M3 Nuts and Bolts with Washers. In this way, you only need a plate specific to your projector, but the rest is universal. (n.b. my projector is quite large, meaning I needed to print the plate in 2 separate sections but this doesn't affect the finished mount once it's bolted together).

Kudos to Wade for the original design, but hopefully you'll find this useful. (n.n.b - it can also be used to mount different items too!)

[Instructions]

  1. Print all parts, 20% infill, no raft or supports
  2. Fasten sections together using M6 Bolts with M6 locking nuts / washers
  3. Fasten the projector plate to the mount using M3 Bolts with M3 locking nuts / washers
  4. Fasten to the ceiling and enjoy move time with the family :-)

Shopping list:

My printer is still new, and I am still fine-tuning it. I had to drill out the LED holes to get them to the proper size. Not sure if you will have to. I also had to file the connection to the fan to make it fit.

Follow the schematic for wiring (courtesy of http://led.linear1.org/led.wiz) There is a 4700 ohm resistor attached to the anode (-) of each LED. They are all then connected in parallel, with each tier consisting of one LED and one resistor. I used bare wire and heat shrink tubing (red) for the positive lead, and put more heat shrink tubing (black) over the resistors and negative leads.

I used the 3d pen to secure the LEDs and the wires to the fan duct. You could use something else, I suppose, if you don't have a 3d pen. I got mine for $20 on wish.com. The same one is available on Amazon for $30.

Once complete, the positive cable connects to one of the V+ terminals on the power supply, the negative cable connects to one of the COM terminals.

description.text:
Parametric Interlocking Mini Drawers

Bin style drawers for components, etc. Now, due to several requests, with 3 compartments, 2 compartments and a single large compartment!

https://youtu.be/m1aATJ88s0A

Dimensions
(75mm by 32mm by 120mm) but you can set the dimensions to anything you like (provided you just install Fusion 360 and punch the numbers in).

If you come across a bug in the resizing feature, let me know and I'll fix it.
Always download the latest files as I will update them with improvements.

Inspiration
I wanted to print custom drawers for my electronic components. The interlocking idea came from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1889761, but they were too small for most components and I imagined they would be very hard to put together if your printer didn't print to the exact size needed. I had also been learning about parametric design in Fusion 360. I decided to do my own design from scratch (this new design has only been printed and tweaked few times). The draw (ho ho ho) with this design is that it is fully parametric - the drawers can be printed to the dimensions you want, so if you need drawers that are long thin and high with extra thick walls, you can make them long thin and high with extra thick walls; it's just a matter of punching the numbers into Fusion - see below.

I have also created a tolerance setting to accommodate less accurate printers and shrinkage. All the interlocking clips and parts that need to fit together and slide are influenced by the Tolerance setting: you can make them tighter (lowering this value) or looser (increasing this value).

Parameter variables you can change in Fusion 360
To create your own custom size STL files download Fusion 360 and open my F3d file.
Then click Modify > Change Parameters (see picture). When done, right click > save as STL.

Parameters that can be set:

  • HousingHeight - external height of housing (excluding little clip at top)
  • HousingWidth - external width
  • HousingDepth - from front to back
  • HousingWallThickness 2.4mm by default gives nice strong housings (haven't tried thinner)
  • Label/Handle Width - this sets the width of the label holder and handle
  • Label Height - sets the height of the holder for labels (not they Y position)
  • Tolerance - I recommend 0.3mm to start with. If it's too tight, try increasing this value to 0.4mm; if it's too loose then reduce it to 0.2mm. In practical 3D printing, a 1cm circle doesn't always go into a 1cm hole - that's where this value comes in very handy. (Keep in mind a horizontal margin of error is effectively halved if it is applied to two surfaces that meet at 45 degrees so you may even want to start at 0.4mm for this value).
  • Drawer dimensions - these are created automatically to suit the dimensions you chose for the housing. The reason for setting the overall dimensions first is that most people with smaller printers want to print the biggest drawers their printer can fit.

Printing with ABS
ABS stands for Absolute Bastard Shrinkage. ABS wants to shrink when it cools and this makes it curl up off the bed - thus printing large flat surfaces like in this design with ABS means pain and suffering..It took me some time to print these properly with ABS. My printer is not an ABS printer by design but it can be done adequately with a bit of science, dedication and patience.

Science
Not rocket science, but ABS shrinking occurs from 80C to 20C. Ideally, you need to print the whole part in an air temperature of 80C degrees! Or as close to that as you can get.

Best settings and strategy for ABS:
Bed: 80C
Nozzle: 245C
Enclosure with minimum heat loss. Metal enclosures are silly as are enclosures with air gaps. I have achieved best results by sitting the printer on a carpet, with a small table on top, and a thick doona/quilt covering everything to the ground. This gives me an printing air temperature of 40C degrees (in a room that is at 20C degrees).
You will also benefit from keeping the print bed heater on for the maximum duty cycle - this means no insulation on the print bed - we want the heat to be lost to the internal air so the heater comes on again.

No air blowing on the part - for me this meant taping up my printers fan outlet to block the air.

Printing the enclosures in ABS
Not too difficult.
Print these standing up, with the back adhered to the print bed. Use a raft of about 18mm. Ensure you are using an enclosure to minimise air cooling drafts"

Old Strategies since abandoned
Printing the drawers in ABS Harder, due to large flat surface.
Print the feet (around 30min), pause, and clip them down with bulldog clips.. (your responsibility to ensure the printhead doesn't hit your clips!) I know people use cans of hairspray and glue and all kinds of crap, but I didn't like doing this and it never really worked for me anyway. So I redesigned the drawers with "mouse ears" or "feet" that can be clipped down mid-print and this has worked really well. You must clip them down at the right time: Soon
Time after they are printed and not before. Taking care that the print head and gantry doesn't hit them! Edit - with the new settings and strategy I don't bother with this crude measure anymore.

An enclosure eliminates splits occurring from contraction forces - so put a cardboard box over your printer if it doesn't have one. Edit - with the new settings and strategy I don't even bother with an enclosure anymore.

Printing with PLA
PLA is generally better for printing with minimum warpage and is probably easier. So try PLA an let me know how you go. I have not tried printing these with PLA yet.

Remixing
You are welcome to remix this if you give credit where it is due. As usual, I have included my original design work F360 files so you don't have to hack your modifications. You can edit all the sketches and design features as you see fit.

Printer:

Malyan M200 (Monoprice select Mini)

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

Optimised for 0.4mm or 0.3mm nozzle (2.4mm and 1.2mm walls)
If you have a different nozzle adjust wall thicknesses to be a multiple of it.

Use raft if you can fit one in, or print some mouse ears to avoid lifting/curling/warping.

Printing the housing standing up on its end requires a tiny bit of support.
Printing the drawer flat requires a tiny pit of support for the handle. So do enable support.

These are all designed in Fusion 360 with a heavy emphasis on user parameters so that anyone can customise the design with very little if any work. Sketches, Extrudes, Patterned Features, Fillets - that is about all.

I ended up making each body a component as an afterthought, not the best practice, I am aware, but I am still of course in the process of learning.

I have tried to name every operation so that if you do need to edit a feature that is not parametrically controlled, the height of the feet for example, you should be able to find the operation with confidence in the timeline, at the bottom of the F360 user interface.

Happy Modding to anyone that wants to.

All parts are correctly oriented in the STL files for printing at medium resolution .2mm, 2 shells, 10% infill. With raft and support.
Do not reorient, trust the "down" face. Do not allow Makerware to auto scale ( where was that thought a good idea to have an option that changes the model, that looks exactly the same as the option to move the model to the bed :-/ )
You can print as many parts as you can fit on your build plate at one time, without warping.
9V battery mount is built into peak. tie wrap mounts are built into the walls throughout to run to led mounts.
Print insert and visor parts in most transparent material you have,
All magnets are placed directly in the parts, without the cups, so you only need the magnets themselves.
Magnets used are 3/8 x 1/10 99K32.03 - 19 off
http://www.leevalley.com/en/wood/page.aspx?p=32065&cat=1,42363,42348
Tension pins throughout model for assembly are 1/8" x 5/8", which are shorter than the original. 240-008 - 46 off, just buy a box of 100.
http://www.spaenaur.com/pdf/sectionE/E107.pdf
Note that the M4 hex head bolts in this version are with 6mm shafts.
Added images at the end showing the tension pins and the magnets for size and example use.

Da die Overlock ja Saugnäpfe als Füße hat steht diese auch recht sicher.

Nach dem Durcken benötigt man noch 4 Magnete.
Ich habe diese hier benutzt:
http://www.pollin.de/shop/dt/NDYwODU1OTk-/Bauelemente_Bauteile/Mechanische_Bauelemente/Montagematerial/Magnet_12x3_mm_6_Stueck.html

Die Bohrungen für die Magnete sind D12,5mm x 3,1mm Groß. Ein Magnet mit D12mmx3mm sollte also passen.
Diesen habe ich einfach mit 2K- Kleber eingeklebt.
Achtet auf die Richtige Polung der Magneten, ansonsten "hüpft" der Auffangbehälter von der Grundplatte.
Ich habe dann den Linken Magneten andersherum eingeklebt wie den rechten Magneten, dadurch habe ich eine Art "Verpolsicherung" und der Behälter kann nur in einer Richtung aufgesetzt werden.

This project is only a drawing, I haven't realized the real thing yet, so, before printing or before milling any single part, check well the Sketchup file and check any possible mistake.

3D printer Scalable XYZ, lifting Z,

Added the Z axis to XY 3D Printer Scalable XY

Z Axis:
-Shaft diameter 20 mm and aluminium holders.
-Linear Bearing LMK 20 (square flange in order to be eased ti aligning the bed).
-Screw: every possible precise screw such as trapezoidal screw.
-Screw nut: you can use a LMK housing (it is possible to change as desired).
Material: from the moment that the bed weight eliminates the backlash it is possible to use every kind of nuts (delrin, bronze ecc.).Probably bronze is the winning choise due to its anty friction property.

The Z axis is studied to be mounted in a precise way without particular tool except for boring the plate where the shafts pass through.

I have raised the bed for the Ones who want to use a silicone heater or similar device under the aluminium bed plate.

Depending on the bed lenght, to use a very thin aluminium plate (i.e. 5mm) you have to apply a couple of reinforcements under or over the plate to avoid deflection.

I have left about 200mm (height) in the lower part of the frame in order to place the electronics and have enough ventilation.

comments.text:
Thanks for posting this. I appreciate it a lot.
You say you didn't know where to get plans. The Union Pacific Historical Society (http://www.uphs.org/CDdrawings.html) sells drawings of the 4000 4-8-8-4, the 4400 0-6-0 (a switch engine) and a bunch of shop drawings. Each of the 3 sets is about $30 for a CD. They're fairly complete. Some of the scans are from rather worn shop drawings, but they're generally quite good. I've been making CAD drawings of the 0-6-0.
Reading the original drawings is an interesting exercise itself. The 0-6-0 in particular is interesting because the drawings were done I believe in the 1920s, so the drawing standards were much different than current standards. Lots of fun to interpret design intent on some of them. The big boy drawings are much more current, and are more readily interpreted.
Again, thanks for posting this. Making the CAD drawings is a fair amount of work.

description.text:
because i did not like the way the extruder cooler was bolted up through so many parts i remixed this shroud to separate the fan from the extruder bolts. i added JST connectors to the fans so the entire shroud can be removed if you need to work on the hotend. Initially there was more airflow horizontally that caused the hotend to be over cooled when the fan was on. It cause temp failure errors and took a few days to figure out what was happening. I thought my control board was at fault. I blocked the outlets so the air is forced down to the part and the hotend works fine now.

The extruder mounting bolts can be replaced with shorter ones. If yous replacement bolt heads will fit in between the fins of the heatsink then subtract the thicknesses of the fan, fan guard and heatsink fins ( do not include the thickness of the heatsink base) to get the new length. If not then you will need to use at least one washer per bolt to straddle the fins of the heatsink. For me this meant using a M3x30mm bolt with a 1 mm thick washer. The space between the shroud and extruder mounting block has clearance for that possibility.
